{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/how-to-make-a-punch-box/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"jmsbrdy"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"2b87e19e-1abf-5590-9f7f-edb823355bf4","excerpt":"I was always told to prize gifts that people had put time and effort into.\nHoping my SO shared the same view, I decided to make her a little something for\nher birthday. Being creatively barren, I attempted plagiarism.","html":"<p>I was always told to prize gifts that people had put time and effort into.\nHoping my SO shared the same view, I decided to make her a little something for\nher birthday.</p>\n<p>Being creatively barren, I attempted plagiarism.</p>\n<!-- excerpt -->\n<p>I remembered seeing <a href=\"http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/leafcutterdesigns/retro-punch-boxes-for-valentines-day\">this Kickstarter project</a> ages ago. Itâ€™s based on an old parlour game: the idea is to conceal little messages inside a nice-looking block, to be popped out with a pencil when the recipient feels like it.</p>\n<p>Now, that Kickstarter project is long since finished but I reckoned I could\nhave a pretty good go at making my own version. Hereâ€™s what I ended up with so\nyou can decide whether to keep reading or not:</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/ac99c/finished.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 88.95705521472392%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Finished product\"\n        title=\"Finished product\"\n        src=\"/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/6aca1/finished.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/d2f63/finished.jpg 163w,\n/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/c989d/finished.jpg 325w,\n/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/6aca1/finished.jpg 650w,\n/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/7c09c/finished.jpg 975w,\n/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/01ab0/finished.jpg 1300w,\n/static/10dccc9b55243c0ec9f73425a7ee75bb/ac99c/finished.jpg 1536w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Finished product</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>I know, it looks like shit doesnâ€™t it? Donâ€™t worry: theyâ€™ll be blown away that\nyou made the effort ðŸ‘Œ.</p>\n<h1 id=\"what-youll-need\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-youll-need\" aria-label=\"what youll need permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What youâ€™ll need</h1>\n<ul>\n<li>three blocks of wood (I used 150mm Ã— 150mm Ã— 20mm, but up to you)</li>\n<li>crÃªpe paper</li>\n<li>two pieces of thick, patterned paper (the same size as the faces of the blocks, e.g. 150mm Ã— 150mm in my case)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cutetape.com/\">washi tape</a></li>\n<li>glue (I used 3M spray mount)</li>\n<li>writing paper</li>\n<li>a drill and ~5mm bit (<em>ideally</em> a drill press but not absolutely required)</li>\n</ul>\n<h1 id=\"what-were-aiming-for\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#what-were-aiming-for\" aria-label=\"what were aiming for permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What weâ€™re aiming for</h1>\n<p>The structure of the block itself is really simple: itâ€™s just a square-ish cut\nof wood with holes drilled through. Rolled up notes are inserted into these\ncylindrical holes, and we stick crÃªpe paper on both faces to hold them in\nplace.</p>\n<p>To make the object a bit more appealing, weâ€™ll add some patterned paper to the\ntop and bottom of the block, with holes pre-punched in it. This makes it easy\nto see where the notes are hiding, and hence where the recipient should poke a\npencil to get one out.</p>\n<p>Lastly, weâ€™ll use washi tape â€“ basically patterned sticky tape â€“ around the\nedge, to keep the crÃªpe nice and tidy.</p>\n<p>This shows a cross-section of the completed box:</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 532px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/3fdee73722f79ba56c73e13773ac6685/89a37/cross-section.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 45.39877300613497%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Cross-section of the box\"\n        title=\"Cross-section of the box\"\n        src=\"/static/3fdee73722f79ba56c73e13773ac6685/89a37/cross-section.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/3fdee73722f79ba56c73e13773ac6685/222b7/cross-section.png 163w,\n/static/3fdee73722f79ba56c73e13773ac6685/ff46a/cross-section.png 325w,\n/static/3fdee73722f79ba56c73e13773ac6685/89a37/cross-section.png 532w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 532px) 100vw, 532px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Cross-section of the box</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h1 id=\"how-to-do-it\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#how-to-do-it\" aria-label=\"how to do it permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How to do it</h1>\n<h2 id=\"creating-the-rolled-up-notes\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#creating-the-rolled-up-notes\" aria-label=\"creating the rolled up notes permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Creating the rolled up notes</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Cut the writing paper into strips</strong>. I found that 210mm long strips (the\nwidth of A4 paper) can be rolled up to fit in a 5mm hole. They should be a\ncouple of millimeters narrower than the wood; e.g. with 20mm thick wood, cut\n18mm wide strips.</li>\n<li><strong>Write your notes on the paper strips</strong>. I canâ€™t really help with this bit!</li>\n<li><strong>Roll the notes up into tight spirals</strong>. I set it up so that as they were\nunrolled, the message gradually appeared as written.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"preparing-the-wood-and-patterned-paper\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#preparing-the-wood-and-patterned-paper\" aria-label=\"preparing the wood and patterned paper permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Preparing the wood and patterned paper</h2>\n<p>What weâ€™re aiming for here is a wood block with holes drilled in it, and patterned paper with holes in it that\nexactly match the layout of holes in the wood block.</p>\n<p>To do that, weâ€™ll sandwich the wood and paper together (using two sacrificial\nwood blocks to prevent tear-out) and drill holes in the wood block <em>and</em>\npatterned paper at the same time. This guarantees the holes in your paper will\nline up with the holes in the block.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Cut out pieces of your patterned paper</strong>. The pieces should be just big\nenough to cover the two largest faces of the block. Mark the paper and\nblocks to remember which one goes on which side.</li>\n<li><strong>Layer your wood blocks and patterned paper</strong>. Wood block, patterned paper,\nwood block, patterned paper, wood block (see below).</li>\n<li><strong>Clamp the wood and paper</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Drill holes through the whole lot</strong>. This is where a drill press would be\nreally handy. If you donâ€™t have one, make sure your drilling at a\nperpendicular!</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Hereâ€™s how the wood-paper sandwich looks before and after drilling:</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 650px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/2574bb384c01de2aba083fe9fcb975c6/4ef49/cross-section-before-drilling.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 47.239263803680984%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Cross-section before drilling\"\n        title=\"Cross-section before drilling\"\n        src=\"/static/2574bb384c01de2aba083fe9fcb975c6/a6d36/cross-section-before-drilling.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/2574bb384c01de2aba083fe9fcb975c6/222b7/cross-section-before-drilling.png 163w,\n/static/2574bb384c01de2aba083fe9fcb975c6/ff46a/cross-section-before-drilling.png 325w,\n/static/2574bb384c01de2aba083fe9fcb975c6/a6d36/cross-section-before-drilling.png 650w,\n/static/2574bb384c01de2aba083fe9fcb975c6/4ef49/cross-section-before-drilling.png 890w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Cross-section before drilling</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h2 id=\"inserting-the-notes\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#inserting-the-notes\" aria-label=\"inserting the notes permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Inserting the notes</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Glue crÃªpe on the bottom of the wood block</strong>. Apply glue to the wood\nrather than the crÃªpe, so that you donâ€™t glue the crÃªpe to the notes\naccidentally. Donâ€™t use too much glue because excess will easily soak\nthrough the paper!</li>\n<li><strong>Insert rolled notes into the holes in your wood</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Glue crÃªpe on the top of the wood block</strong>. Again, apply glue to the wood\nrather than the crÃªpe.</li>\n<li><strong>Stick washi tape round the edge of the block</strong>. A sharp knife makes it\neasier to get the ends of the tape to sit close to each other without\noverlapping.</li>\n<li><strong>Stick patterned paper on the top and bottom of the block</strong>. Use the marks\nyou made to ensure you have the right piece of paper, in the right\norientation, on the right face.</li>\n<li><strong>Leave to dry</strong>.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>To ensure that there wasnâ€™t an unsightly crÃªpe paper join at the edges of the\nbox, I cut the bottom piece of paper too big and wrapped the excess up and\naround the sides of the box. That way the top piece of crÃªpe met and overlapped\nwith the bottom piece.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Home-made present: how to make a punch box","description":null,"keywords":["diy","craft","present"],"coverImage":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/how-to-make-a-punch-box/"}}}